{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517750"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:56:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12833"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12833"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.07,0.61,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53659"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39122"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3542"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9149"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16153"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53659"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents with a two week history of a generalised body ache, with associated fatigue and a low-grade fever. Her symptoms have now worsened and she has developed severe neck pain and swelling. Her current symptoms include palpitations, headache, excessive sweating and diarrhoea. She had an uncomplicated caesarean section two years ago. Her blood pressure is 155/105 mmHg, pulse 120/min and temperature 37.9\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. On examination of her neck her thyroid is not visible, but it is palpable and tender. Laboratory investigation results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR: 60mm/hr (0-30).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein): 100mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 120g/L (130-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeucocytes: 9.3 x 10^9 cells/L (4.0-11.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET4: 35nmol/L (12-20).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET3: 5.4nmol/L (1.3-3.1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETSH: 0.05mIU/L (0.4-4.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid peroxidase antibody: 15 IU/mL (\u0026lt;35).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid receptor antibody: Negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis","Graves\u0027 disease","Postpartum thyroiditis","Subacute thyroiditis","Suppurative thyroiditis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has \u003Cstrong\u003Esubacute thyroiditis \u003C/strong\u003Edue to the characteristic finding of a painful thyroid gland along with malaise, fatigue, low-grade fever and signs and symptoms related to hyperthyroidism. The laboratory findings in this patient are also characteristic of subacute thyroiditis with raised ESR, CRP, normal or mildly elevated leucocyte count, raised t4 and t3 and very low or undetectable TSH and normal thyroid peroxidase antibody titres. Painful subacute thyroiditis, which is a self-limited inflammatory disorder, is the most common cause of thyroid pain. Around 50% of patients have symptoms of thyrotoxicosis. After thyrotoxicosis, a state of normal thyroid function follows, which is followed by a state of hypothyroidism. Although thyroid function normalises spontaneously in 95% of patients over a period of 6 to 12 months, residual hypothyroidism will persist in 5% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most common type of thyroiditis and is characterised by the presence of high serum thyroid antibody concentrations and goitre. It is also usually associated with a normal ESR and a hypothyroid picture of thyroid function tests. These patients less commonly present with hyperthyroidism initially due to the release of thyroid hormone with the thyroiditis, before progressing to permanent hypothyroidism. This is a reasonable differential to consider, but with (-) anti-TPO and because subacute thyroiditis is generally a more common cause of hyperthyroidism, Hashimoto\u0027s is not the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGraves\u0027 disease \u003C/strong\u003Eis an autoimmune disorder characterised by hyperthyroidism, usually presenting symptoms such as weight loss, palpitations, tremors and heat intolerance. Patients with Graves\u0027 disease may have diffuse thyroid enlargement and ophthalmopathy, but it is not usually associated with a painful thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPostpartum thyroiditis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a plausible option in this scenario, it is characterised by lymphocytic infiltration of the thyroid gland and usually presents with a hyperthyroid picture, but it usually occurs within around six months post-partum and is also associated with high anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies. The thyroid gland is not usually tender to palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppurative thyroiditis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan present in a patient with an acutely-ill picture with fever, dysphagia, anterior neck pain and tenderness, it is usually preceded by an infection. Thyroid function is usually normal, but the patient can present with both hyper and hypothyroid pictures. It is associated with a high leucocyte count due to the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subacute thyroiditis can present with generalised malaise, body aches, low-grade fever, signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism and a painful thyroid gland."],"references":["Acute and Subacute, and Riedel\u2019s Thyroiditis Majesty P, Hennessey JV. Feingold PR. Subacute Thyroiditis. [2000.Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.2000;2022 Jul 25."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39122"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39122"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-23T22:02:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-23T22:03:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5276"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53659"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7